/organizationName><role>Originator</role></originator><abstract><paragraph>Surveys of streams consisting of physical, chemical and biological data related to a variety of different project objectives.  Basic approach is to develop biological indicators for different types of stream pollution, stress, or disturbance, using aquatic invertebrate communities as the main way of detecting ecological impact.  The topics that have been addressed by this research include the following: development of stream quality biocriteria (sampling of reference sites in the Lahontan region of the eastern Sierra Nevada), livestock grazing impacts, sedimentation and TMDL development (Squaw Creek), acid mine drainage (Leviathan Mine), channel restoration monitoring (Tahoe basin), introduced trout impacts on stream communities (Yosemite National Park), and forest management practices (Sierra National Forest).  Physical data include channel, substrate, and flow features; chemical data include nutrients, oxygen, conductivity, pH, temperature, and turbidity; biological data include algal periphyton densities and species, organic matter (fine and coarse particulate fraction), and aquatic invertebrate community structure.  Watersheds encompass the following: upper Owens River, Mono Basin, Walker River, Carson River, Tahoe Basin, and Lower Truckee River.  Approximately 400 stream surveys are represented</paragraph></abstract><keywordSet><keyword>biological indicators</keyword><keywordThesaurus>none</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword>stream ecology</keyword><keywordThesaurus>none</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword keywordType="place">Sierra Nevada, CA</keyword><keywordThesaurus>none</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword>water quality</keyword><keywordThesaurus>GCMD</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword>benthic index</keyword><keywordThesaurus>GCMD</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword>aquatic invertebrates</keyword><keywor